## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort to Cooperative Cancellation

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow.

In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`). The replacement is `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If the work itself needs to cooperate with cancellation

The version above times out the *wait*, but the work lambda keeps running in the background (just like the old `Thread.Abort` version, except there's no forced kill). To make work **actually stop**, pass the token through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — work checks the token:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If the lambda ignores the token, it keeps running after timeout. Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` owns internal timers — always wrap in `using`. The original code had no disposal concerns. |
| **Catching the wrong exception** | Old code caught `ThreadAbortException`. New code must catch `OperationCanceledException`. The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard distinguishes timeout from external cancellation. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort` has no equivalent** | The original catch-and-continue pattern (`ResetAbort`) is replaced by checking `token.IsCancellationRequested` and deciding whether to proceed. |
| **Blocking calls inside work** | `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous I/O, etc. won't respond to the token. Replace with `Task.Delay(ms, token)` or async I/O overloads. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you can't modify the work to accept a token, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only way to forcibly stop uncooperative code in modern .NET. |

### What was removed and why

| .NET Framework API | Status in .NET 8 | Replacement used |
|-|-|-|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` / `CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Obsolete `SYSLIB0006` | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| Manual `Thread` + `Join(timeout)` | Still works but unnecessary | `Task.Run` + `Task.WaitAsync(token)` |
